    "planet": "",
    "sign": "salutogenesis",
    "house": "",
    "traditional_en": "The question most commonly posed to psychological crisis is: what caused this, and how do we eliminate it? A different question — one that decades of resilience research have been building toward — is: what allows certain people to move through severe disruption and arrive at a greater degree of integration on the other side? This is the salutogenic question, and it points toward something the strictly pathological model misses: that the capacity for acute distress and the capacity for deep development often run in the same channel, drawing on the same constitutional sensitivity.\n\nMental health challenges and what the tradition calls spiritual emergencies do not always point primarily toward breakdown. In many biographical cases, they represent a developmental threshold that the current structure of the self is not yet equipped to cross — and the disruption is the pressure of what is attempting to come through meeting a structure not yet capable of receiving it. This does not mean all suffering is instructive, or that crisis is reliably growth in disguise. Some crises are simply damaging, and that must be named honestly. The distinction lies in what resources accompany the disruption: whether there is anything — relational, contemplative, embodied — capable of holding the intensity without either suppressing it prematurely or being entirely overwhelmed by it.\n\nThe chart can indicate constitutionally sensitive zones: configurations that predispose toward heightened receptivity, porous boundaries, and depth-experience that the ordinary social world is not structured to hold. These are not pathological markers. They describe a nervous system and soul-constitution that require correspondingly more substantial support structures — and that, when those structures are present, are capable of a degree of development not otherwise available.",
    "evolutionary_en": "",
    "developmental_en": "",
    "aphorism_en": "The capacity to be wounded and the capacity to be transformed are not different capacities."
