    "traditional_en": "The word 'mission' carries the weight of the extraordinary — the single defining purpose that justifies a life, legible from the outside, pointing unambiguously toward something unique. The chart rarely encodes something that clean. What it encodes instead is a set of intersecting developments that, read together, suggest three distinct layers of purposive activity working simultaneously throughout a biography, each real, each demanding, none entirely reducible to the others.\n\nThe outer mission is the most visible: the work that appears in the world, the contribution that can be named and pointed to across a life. It tends to be read through the Midheaven, the tenth house, and the house of the Sun — the arenas in which the person's developed capacities meet what the surrounding world genuinely needs. This layer is where biographical legacy becomes most legible to those who come after.\n\nThe inner mission is the transformation of the self as a development project in its own right: the specific soul-work this lifetime's configuration requires, independent of whether it is ever visible to the outside world. It is read through the harder aspects — the Saturn configurations, the nodal axis, the Pluto and Chiron placements — and it is often where the most consequential work of a life actually occurs, even when nothing external appears to reflect it.\n\nThe cosmic mission is the most difficult to name without tipping into grandiosity, so this report approaches it carefully: it is the particular way this individual's development — outer and inner together — participates in what the broader human project is attempting to work out in this specific historical moment. The chart suggests how that participation takes form.",
